      Frank!
   =20
 =20

In 2021, JPMorgan Chase & Co. paid $175 million to acquire Frank, a financi=
al technology company that helps students fill out college financial aid fo=
rms. It is not obvious why this would be a lucrative business for JPMorgan,=
 or Frank, but that was not really the point of the acquisition. The point =
of the acquisition is that helping students fill out college financial aid =
forms, while not itself lucrative,=C2=A0might help you build long-term fina=
ncial relationships with them at an early and impressionable point in their=
 lives. If Frank helps a student fill out her financial aid forms, she migh=
t like Frank, so when Frank emails her and says =E2=80=9Chey now that you=
=E2=80=99re in college you should set up a checking account, here=E2=80=99s=
 one,=E2=80=9D she might open the checking account =E2=80=94=C2=A0at JPMorg=
an =E2=80=94=C2=A0that Frank recommends. Later, she might get her mortgage =
through a Frank recommendation. JPMorgan was buying Frank=E2=80=99s custome=
r relationships, so that it could use them to sell financial products that=
=C2=A0were=C2=A0lucrative.
That is, in some sense, JPMorgan paid Frank $175 million for an email list.=
 As the proprietor of an email list myself, I have some interest=C2=A0in th=
is transaction.
It went poorly. Frank=E2=80=99s founder, Charlie Javice, kept running Frank=
 after it became part of JPMorgan, but in November 2022 JPMorgan fired=C2=
=A0her, and now   she and JPMorgan are suing each other. Here is  Javice=E2=
=80=99s lawsuit against JPMorgan, which basically demands that the bank pay=
 her legal fees; her lawyer is Alex Spiro, who is also Elon Musk=E2=80=99s =
lawyer, so I assume he=E2=80=99s expensive. Here is  JPMorgan=E2=80=99s law=
suit against Javice, which accuses her of fraud: The gist of it is that JPM=
organ now says that Frank=E2=80=99s email list, which it paid $175 million =
for, was fake.
One thing that the two lawsuits agree on is that, when JPMorgan took over F=
rank, its first order of business was to spam Frank=E2=80=99s customers wit=
h JPMorgan marketing. Here=E2=80=99s how JPMorgan puts it:

In January 2022, after JPMC acquired Frank, JPMC began work on a marketing =
campaign to test the quality of Frank=E2=80=99s customer account list and t=
he receptiveness of these customers to JPMC=E2=80=99s products and services=
. To facilitate this marketing campaign, JPMC asked Javice and [Frank Chief=
 Growth Officer Olivier] Amar to provide Frank=E2=80=99s user list so that =
JPMC could send the marketing test by email. =E2=80=A6
JPMC reached out via email to a random sample of the list Frank provided =
=E2=80=93 approximately 400,000 purported customers of Frank =E2=80=93 with=
 offers to open Chase checking or savings accounts. Of those 400,000, only =
103 even clicked through to Frank=E2=80=99s website.

As an email list proprietor, I can say: not a great click rate. Here=E2=80=
=99s Javice=E2=80=99s version:
Chase undermined Frank=E2=80=99s value by pursuing poorly conceived busines=
s plans focused on monetizing student FAFSA=C2=AE data and conducting direc=
t marketing campaigns aimed at Frank=E2=80=99s historical customers. The pr=
oposed business plans disregarded the regulatory environment in which the f=
inancial aid platform operated, failed to capitalize on Ms. Javice=E2=80=99=
s past successes, and discounted the very skills for which JPMorgan Bank hi=
red her. More specifically, the new team focused primarily on mining the pe=
rsonal information of Frank=E2=80=99s legacy customers to blast them with m=
arketing emails promoting consumer financial products, including credit car=
ds and personal loans.=C2=A0
In Javice=E2=80=99s story, she objected to JPMorgan=E2=80=99s efforts to ma=
rket to her customers, for regulatory and, one assumes, aesthetic reasons; =
JPMorgan=C2=A0retaliated by subjecting her =E2=80=9Cto overzealous internal=
 investigations and fishing expeditions=E2=80=9D and eventually firing her.
JPMorgan=E2=80=99s story is considerably more interesting. In its story, th=
e 0.026% click rate on the test email was evidence that Javice=E2=80=99s em=
ail list was not what JPMorgan had hoped for. So it =E2=80=9Cinitiated a co=
mprehensive investigation into Frank and the Merger,=E2=80=9D mostly by rea=
ding through Javice=E2=80=99s old emails, which are now on JPMorgan=E2=80=
=99s servers.
  [1]
 Oh boy did that turn up some good stuff!
During due diligence for the merger, Javice told JPMorgan that Frank had 4.=
25 million users. =E2=80=9CUsers,=E2=80=9D to JPMorgan, seems to have meant=
 something close to =E2=80=9Cpeople we can send emails to=E2=80=9D:

At an initial July 2021 meeting, Javice told JPMC that Frank had significan=
t engagement with college-aged students, a market segment that JPMC wanted =
to grow. Javice stated that Frank had 4.25 million users, expressly definin=
g a =E2=80=9Cuser=E2=80=9D as an individual who created a Frank account by =
entering a first name, last name, email, and phone number on Frank=E2=80=99=
s website. =E2=80=A6
Based on the July 21 meeting and the data room materials, JPMC confirmed Fr=
ank=E2=80=99s definition of its customers base, namely, customers are users=
 who created a Frank account. Thereafter, as part of due diligence on Javic=
e=E2=80=99s 4.265 million customer account claim, JPMC made an unambiguous =
request to Javice for a list of Frank=E2=80=99s customer accounts that incl=
uded important data, such as first names, last names, dates of birth, phone=
 numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses. =E2=80=A6
Specifically, JPMC sought to confirm its thesis that Frank=E2=80=99s acquis=
ition of 4.265 million customer accounts demonstrated that=C2=A0Frank had c=
reated momentum, growth, and scale by developing meaningful relationships w=
ith millions of students. That momentum, growth, and scale, JPMC believed, =
indicated that Frank was a proven acquisition machine for college-aged stud=
ents and would continue =E2=80=93 and even increase =E2=80=93 its customer =
account base once Frank merged with and into JPMC. If Frank=E2=80=99s custo=
mer base existed, JPMC could proceed with the deal.

But, JPMorgan now says, Frank only really had about 300,000 customer accoun=
ts. So Javice allegedly asked a Frank engineer to make up a fake list. It d=
id not go great:

She sent Frank=E2=80=99s Director of Engineering an email with a link to an=
