  [1] =E2=80=9CJPMC has all the emails showing the fraud because Javice and=
 Amar used Frank=E2=80=99s email accounts to create the Fake Customer List =
and the email accounts now belong to JPMC following the Merger.=E2=80=9D=20


  [2] I used to do mergers and acquisitions work at a law firm that rather =
famously  does not bill by the hour. My most pleasing task was sending clie=
nt bills that were like =E2=80=9CServices rendered =E2=80=A6 $4,000,000.=E2=
=80=9D=20


  [3] Why a consultant? JPMorgan says: =E2=80=9CJavice also cited privacy c=
oncerns in sharing Frank=E2=80=99s customer data directly with JPMC. After =
numerous internal conversations, and in order to allay Javice=E2=80=99s con=
cerns, JPMC agreed to use a third-party data management vendor, Acxiom, to =
validate Frank=E2=80=99s customer information rather than providing the per=
sonal identifying information directly to JPMC.=E2=80=9D


  [4] This is probably boring to most people, but there is a strange interl=
ude on pages 30 to 34 of JPMorgan=E2=80=99s complaint where they discuss th=
e merger agreement in great detail. Specifically, they discuss a number of =
representations and covenants that Frank made in the merger agreement =E2=
=80=94 things like it =E2=80=9Chas conducted its business and operated its =
properties in the ordinary course of business consistent with past practice=
=E2=80=9D and will =E2=80=9Cuse commercially reasonable efforts to maintain=
 and preserve the =E2=80=A6 goodwill of the business=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C=
there has not been a =E2=80=A6 misuse or misappropriation of any Trade Secr=
ets=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 and argue that this alleged fraud breached those pro=
visions of the merger agreement. This is kind of weird! The most natural wa=
y to describe the alleged fraud here is not that it was a *misuse of trade =
secrets*. The implication that you have to take from it is that the merger =
agreement did *not* say things like =E2=80=9Cthe information Frank provided=
 in due diligence is substantially correct=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CFrank has 4=
.25 million customers=E2=80=9D or whatever. (A further implication is that =
the merger agreement probably had an =E2=80=9Centire agreement=E2=80=9D cla=
use saying that JPMorgan did not rely on anything outside of the agreement =
in signing the deal.) And so JPMorgan has to assert that Javice breached th=
e merger agreement in some weird indirect way, that inventing a customer li=
st was a misuse of trade secrets or not in the ordinary course or whatever.=
 Oddly it is a little reminiscent of   Elon Musk=E2=80=99s efforts last yea=
r to get out of his deal with Twitter Inc.: Musk claimed that Twitter was l=
ying about how many bot accounts there were, but in fact Twitter never made=
 any representations at all about the number of bots, so Musk had to make w=
eird indirect claims about how the bot stuff somehow violated the merger ag=
reement. There, too, though, he also made separate claims of *fraud*; the i=
ntuition is that even if he couldn=E2=80=99t get out of the merger agreemen=
t due to a breach of the contract, maybe he could because Twitter had pulle=
d an enormous con to trick him into signing. This did not work for him, bec=
ause it was just obviously untrue. Here, uh =E2=80=A6 I mean I would think =
JPMorgan could argue the same sort of thing? Possibly with more success?


  [5] One obvious answer is "because it gives prosecutors more information =
about his defense and more time to figure out how to undermine it." But pre=
sumably they have a pretty good idea anyway.


  [6] Frustratingly, it is not laid out as a balance sheet; I think you hav=
e to read the first line =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9CCustomer balances=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94 as the liabilities and the other lines =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9CWallet bal=
ances,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CFBO bank balances,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CCorp balances=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CReg bank balances=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 as the assets.=
=20


  [7] He is also making the case that FTX could have been saved? =E2=80=9CI=
 think it=E2=80=99s likely that FTX could have made all customers whole if =
a concerted effort had been made to raise liquidity. There were billions of=
 dollars of funding offers when Mr. Ray took over, and more than $4b that c=
ame in after. If FTX had been given a few weeks to raise the necessary liqu=
idity, I believe it would have been able to make customers substantially wh=
ole.=E2=80=9D I mean? Okay?


  [8] I am sorry to   keep bringing it up, but this story is particularly u=
ndermined by the time, last April, when Bankman-Fried   described yield far=
ming to me on the Odd Lots podcast. He said: =E2=80=9CIf everyone kind of n=
ow thinks that this box token is worth about a billion dollar market cap, t=
hat's what people are pricing it at and sort of has that market cap. Everyo=
ne's gonna mark to market. In fact, you can even finance this, right? You p=
ut X token in a borrow lending protocol and borrow dollars with it. If you =
think it's worth like less than two thirds of that, you could even just lik=
e put some in there, take the dollars out. Never, you know, give the dollar=
s back.=E2=80=9D And I said: =E2=80=9CYou're just like, well, I'm in the Po=
nzi business and it's pretty good.=E2=80=9D My point here is just that he d=
idn=E2=80=99t *sound* like a naive true believer in the robust long-term va=
lue of FTT or Solana or whatever, or in the wisdom of lending against it.


  [9] In fact the amortization is constant interest rate amortization rathe=
r than straight-line, meaning that you deduct less in early years and more =
in later years, but it adds up to the same thing (you deduct $100 over 10 y=
ears). The $5.60 per year of taxable income is an average: You pay more tha=
n that in earlier years (when you have gotten back less of your money and s=
o really are getting 3.6% interest on $200ish of investment) and less in la=
ter years (when you have gotten back much of your money and are getting 3.6=
% interest on $100ish of remaining principal).


  [10] Treasury  reports that it has about $23 billion of marketable securi=
ties outstanding as of last February, and Nasdaq reports that their average=
 maturity is 62 months. So that=E2=80=99s an average of $370 billion of mat=
urities a month.


