</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2021, JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. paid $175 mi=
llion to acquire Frank, a financial technology company that helps students =
fill out college financial aid forms. It is not obvious why this would be a=
 lucrative business for JPMorgan, or Frank, but that was not really the poi=
nt of the acquisition. The point of the acquisition is that helping student=
s fill out college financial aid forms, while not itself lucrative,=C2=A0mi=
ght help you build long-term financial relationships with them at an early =
and impressionable point in their lives. If Frank helps a student fill out =
her financial aid forms, she might <em>like </em>Frank, so when Frank email=
s her and says =E2=80=9Chey now that you=E2=80=99re in college you should s=
et up a checking account, here=E2=80=99s one,=E2=80=9D she might open the c=
hecking account =E2=80=94=C2=A0at JPMorgan =E2=80=94=C2=A0that Frank recomm=
ends. Later, she might get her mortgage through a Frank recommendation. JPM=
organ was buying Frank=E2=80=99s customer relationships, so that it could u=
se them to sell financial products that=C2=A0<em>were=C2=A0</em>lucrative.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, in some sense, JPMorgan paid Frank $1=
75 million for an email list. As the proprietor of an email list myself, I =
have some interest=C2=A0in this transaction.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It went poorly. Frank=E2=80=99s founder, Charl=
ie Javice, kept running Frank after it became part of JPMorgan, but in Nove=
mber 2022 JPMorgan fired=C2=A0her, and now <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30232666.268518/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTEvanBtb3JnYW4tc2F5cy1pdC13YXMtZGVmcmF1ZGVkL=
WluLTE3NS1taWxsaW9uLWZyYW5rLWFjcXVpc2l0aW9uP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTIyM19NT05FWVNU=
VUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDE=
xMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91250a9c" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  she and JPMorgan are suing each other</a>. Here is <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30232666.268518/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMu=
YndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JfMnB1ckI3VzRsby92MA/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2d217e4d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Javice=E2=80=99s lawsuit against JP=
Morgan</a>, which basically demands that the bank pay her legal fees; her l=
awyer is Alex Spiro, who is also Elon Musk=E2=80=99s lawyer, so I assume he=
=E2=80=99s expensive. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/30232666.268518/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXN=
lcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JObE5WVGwuNnloOC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB47e917=
28" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> JPMorgan=E2=80=99s lawsuit against Javice</a>, which accuses =
her of fraud: The gist of it is that JPMorgan now says that Frank=E2=80=99s=
 email list, which it paid $175 million for, was fake.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that the two lawsuits agree on is th=
at, when JPMorgan took over Frank, its first order of business was to spam =
Frank=E2=80=99s customers with JPMorgan marketing. Here=E2=80=99s how JPMor=
gan puts it:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In January 2022, after JPMC acquired Frank, JP=
MC began work on a marketing campaign to test the quality of Frank=E2=80=99=
s customer account list and the receptiveness of these customers to JPMC=E2=
=80=99s products and services. To facilitate this marketing campaign, JPMC =
asked Javice and [Frank Chief Growth Officer Olivier] Amar to provide Frank=
=E2=80=99s user list so that JPMC could send the marketing test by email. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMC reached out via email to a random sample =
of the list Frank provided =E2=80=93 approximately 400,000 purported custom=
ers of Frank =E2=80=93 with offers to open Chase checking or savings accoun=
ts. Of those 400,000, only 103 even clicked through to Frank=E2=80=99s webs=
ite.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As an email list proprietor, I can say: not a =
great click rate. Here=E2=80=99s Javice=E2=80=99s version:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chase undermined Frank=E2=80=99s v=
alue by pursuing poorly conceived business plans focused on monetizing stud=
ent FAFSA=C2=AE data and conducting direct marketing campaigns aimed at Fra=
nk=E2=80=99s historical customers. The proposed business plans disregarded =
the regulatory environment in which the financial aid platform operated, fa=
iled to capitalize on Ms. Javice=E2=80=99s past successes, and discounted t=
he very skills for which JPMorgan Bank hired her. More specifically, the ne=
w team focused primarily on mining the personal information of Frank=E2=80=
=99s legacy customers to blast them with marketing emails promoting consume=
r financial products, including credit cards and personal loans.=C2=A0</p><=
/blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Javice=E2=80=99s story, she objected to JPM=
organ=E2=80=99s efforts to market to her customers, for regulatory and, one=
 assumes, aesthetic reasons; JPMorgan=C2=A0retaliated by subjecting her =E2=
=80=9Cto overzealous internal investigations and fishing expeditions=E2=80=
=9D and eventually firing her.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan=E2=80=99s story is considerably more =
interesting. In its story, the 0.026% click rate on the test email was evid=
ence that Javice=E2=80=99s email list was not what JPMorgan had hoped for. =
So it =E2=80=9Cinitiated a comprehensive investigation into Frank and the M=
erger,=E2=80=9D mostly by reading through Javice=E2=80=99s old emails, whic=
h are now on JPMorgan=E2=80=99s servers.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Oh boy did that turn up some good stuff!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During due diligence for the merger, Javice to=
ld JPMorgan that Frank had 4.25 million users. =E2=80=9CUsers,=E2=80=9D to =
JPMorgan, seems to have meant something close to =E2=80=9Cpeople we can sen=
d emails to=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At an initial July 2021 meeting, Javice told J=
PMC that Frank had significant engagement with college-aged students, a mar=
ket segment that JPMC wanted to grow. Javice stated that Frank had 4.25 mil=
lion users, expressly defining a =E2=80=9Cuser=E2=80=9D as an individual wh=
o created a Frank account by entering a first name, last name, email, and p=
hone number on Frank=E2=80=99s website. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Based on the July 21 meeting and the data room=
 materials, JPMC confirmed Frank=E2=80=99s definition of its customers base=
, namely, customers are users who created a Frank account. Thereafter, as p=
art of due diligence on Javice=E2=80=99s 4.265 million customer account cla=
im, JPMC made an unambiguous request to Javice for a list of Frank=E2=80=99=
s customer accounts that included important data, such as first names, last=
 names, dates of birth, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email address=
es. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically, JPMC sought to confirm its thesi=
s that Frank=E2=80=99s acquisition of 4.265 million customer accounts demon=
strated that=C2=A0Frank had created momentum, growth, and scale by developi=
ng meaningful relationships with millions of students. That momentum, growt=
h, and scale, JPMC believed, indicated that Frank was a proven acquisition =
machine for college-aged students and would continue =E2=80=93 and even inc=
rease =E2=80=93 its customer account base once Frank merged with and into J=
PMC. If Frank=E2=80=99s customer base existed, JPMC could proceed with the =
deal.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, JPMorgan now says, Frank only really had =
about 300,000 customer accounts. So Javice allegedly asked a Frank engineer=
 to make up a fake list. It did not go great:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">She sent Frank=E2=80=99s Director of Engineeri=
ng an email with a link to an article entitled =E2=80=9CGenerating Tabular =
Synthetic Data Using GANs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The article notes that =E2=80=9C[t=
]he goal is to generate synthetic data that is similar to the actual data i=
n terms of statistics and demographics.=E2=80=9D The article suggests that =
=E2=80=9Cit[=E2=80=99]s fairly simpl[e] to use GANs to generate synthetic d=
ata where the actual data is sensitive in nature and can=E2=80=99t be share=
d publicly.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Javice, Amar, and the Director of Engineering =
then had a Zoom meeting during which Javice and Amar asked the Director of =
Engineering to help them create a synthetic list of=C2=A0customer data. She=
 asked the Director of Engineering if he could help her take a known set of=
 FAFSA application data and use it to artificially augment a much larger se=
t of anonymous data that her systems had collected over time. The Director =
of Engineering questioned whether creating and using such a data set was le=
gal, but Javice tried to assure the engineer by claiming that this was perf=
ectly acceptable in an investment situation and she did not believe that an=
yone would end up in an =E2=80=9Corange jumpsuit=E2=80=9D over this project=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Director of Engineering was not persuaded =
and told Javice and Amar that he would not perform the task and only would =
send them the file containing Frank=E2=80=99s actual users, which amounted =
to approximately 293,000 individuals at that time.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Aieee, this is not legal advice, but if your b=
oss is prone to using the phrase =E2=80=9Corange jumpsuit=E2=80=9D you shou=
ld quit! And probably go claim your whistle-blower reward while you=E2=80=
=99re at it. Anyway Javice then allegedly =E2=80=9Csought help from externa=
l sources=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Javice then turned to a data scien=
ce professor at a New York City area college (the =E2=80=9CData Science Pro=
fessor=E2=80=9D) who advertised his =E2=80=9Ccreative solutions=E2=80=9D to=
 data problems. Javice provided the Data Science Professor a list of 293,19=
2 individuals who had started or submitted a FAFSA application through Fran=
k. She then directed the Data Science Professor to use=C2=A0=E2=80=9Csynthe=
tic data=E2=80=9D techniques to create 4.265 million customer names, email =
addresses, birthdays, and other personal information based on the list Javi=
ce supplied.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The professor allegedly created the list, with=
 lots of hilarious guidance along the way that JPMorgan now has:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Regarding creating physical addresses, the Dat=
a Science Professor wrote to Javice, =E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t seem to find =
addresses in my raw files . . . . Should I attempt to fabricate them?=E2=80=
=9D Javice responded =E2=80=9CI just wouldn=E2=80=99t want the street to no=
t exist in the state.=E2=80=9D Later, the Data Science Professor determined=
 that =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98real addresses=E2=80=99 may not be doable,=E2=80=9D=
 and Javice responded =E2=80=9CIf we can=E2=80=99t do real addresses what[=
=E2=80=99]s the best we can do for that?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Javice was particularly concerned with the ema=
il addresses, asking the Data Science Professor =E2=80=9Cwill the fake emai=
ls look real with an eye check or better to use unique ID?=E2=80=9D He resp=
onded =E2=80=9C[t]hey will look fake,=E2=80=9D at which point Javice agreed=
 to use a =E2=80=9Cunique ID=E2=80=9D instead.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eventually the list was done and the professor=
 sent Frank an invoice for $13,300, listing his hours devoted to tasks like=
 =E2=80=9Ccollege major generation.=E2=80=9D This was not the invoice Javic=
e wanted, so:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response to the initial invoice, Javice dem=
anded that he remove all the details admitting to how they had created fake=
 customers =E2=80=93 and added a $4,700 bonus. In an email to the Data Scie=
nce Professor at 12:39 p.m. on August 5, 2021, Javice wrote: =E2=80=9Csend =
the invoice back at $18k and just one line item for data analysis.=E2=80=9D=
 In total, Javice paid the Data Science Professor over $800 per hour for hi=
s work creating the Fake Customer List, which is 270% of his usual hourly r=
ate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Data Science Professor provided Javice the=
 revised invoice via email seven minutes later at 12:46 p.m., commenting =
=E2=80=9CWow. Thank you. Here is the new invoice.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah I mean a general lesson here is that you =
want to be in the sort of business that sends one-line invoices, not the so=
rt of business that bills by the sixth of the hour.<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This basically worked: Frank sent its list of =
4,265,085 customers to JPMorgan=E2=80=99s third-party due diligence consult=
ant,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> the consultant okayed it, JPMorgan was satisfied and they signed the m=
erger agreement. But you can see how this would be a problem for Frank in t=
he medium term: It had a list of 4 million customers with fake email addres=
ses, and JPMorgan was basically buying it so it could send emails to that l=
ist. If the email addresses were all fake, JPMorgan would notice immediatel=
y. So Frank allegedly=C2=A0<em>went out and bought an email list:</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the exact same time Javice was working with=
 the Data Science Professor on the Fake Customer List, Amar separately reac=
hed out to ASL Marketing, Inc. (=E2=80=9CASL=E2=80=9D), a marketing firm th=
at purports to have =E2=80=9Cthe most comprehensive, accurate and responsiv=
e data of high school students, college students and young adults available=
 anywhere.=E2=80=9D Amar caused Frank to purchase a list of 4.5 million stu=
dents from ASL for a cost of $105,000 (the =E2=80=9CASL List=E2=80=9D) on t=
he same day Javice transferred the Fake Customer List to the third-party ve=
ndor for validation. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Amar and Javice would have had no reason to bu=
y a list of 4.5 million college students if Frank actually had the number o=
f customer accounts that Javice represented to JPMC and provided to Acxiom.=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The ASL list had about 4.5 million names, but =
only about 2 million of them had email addresses, so Javice allegedly went =
to another company to try to buy the relevant email addresses:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Javice again engaged the Data Science Professo=
r to work with another third-party vendor, Enformion, LLC (=E2=80=9CEnformi=
on=E2=80=9D), to obtain additional email addresses to add-on to the individ=
uals in the ASL List. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After receiving the data, Enformion ran the AS=
L List through its databases in an attempt to find matching additional data=
, including email addresses. Enformion then provided those matches to the D=
ata Science Professor.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Upon information and belief, Javice and the Da=
ta Science Professor=E2=80=99s first request to Enformion was to provide em=
ail addresses based on the existing full names and addresses, but that prov=
ided a limited number of matches. Upon information and belief, Javice decid=
ed to instruct Enformion to match against just last names and addresses, wh=
ich could generate email addresses of siblings, parents, and other family m=
embers of the individual on the ASL List, even if the email affiliated with=
 the exact individual on the ASL List could not be found.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ultimately, Javice and the Data Science Profes=
sor obtained at least one email address for approximately 1.9 million of th=
e 4.5 million individuals on the ASL List from Enformion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Frank paid Enformion $70,000 for this. So, in =
essence, it paid a total of $175,000 for a list of email addresses, and the=
n=C2=A0<em>sold that list to JPMorgan for $175 million</em>, for a perfect =
99,900% return on its investment.=C2=A0What an arbitrage! The intuition is =
that a list of 4 million email addresses with whom you have a warm customer=
 relationship is worth roughly 1,000 times as much as a list of 4 million r=
andom email addresses that you scraped up from the dregs of the internet. J=
avice allegedly scraped up these addresses from the dregs of the internet, =
dressed them up in Frank=E2=80=99s warm customer relationships, and sold th=
em to JPMorgan at a 1,000x markup. Incredible stuff.<a class=3D"footnote-in=
dex" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; disp=
lay: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
