!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">fateful tweet</a>, following =
an extremely effective months-long PR campaign against FTX=E2=80=93and the =
crash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Up until that final crash in November, QQQ had=
 moved roughly half as much as Alameda=E2=80=99s portfolio, and BTC/ETH had=
 moved roughly 80% as much=E2=80=93meaning that Alameda=E2=80=99s hedges (Q=
QQ/BTC/ETH), to the extent they existed, had worked.=C2=A0 Unfortunately th=
e hedges hadn=E2=80=99t been sufficiently large until after the 3AC crash=
=E2=80=93but as of October 2022, they finally were.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the November crash was a targeted attack o=
n assets held by Alameda, not a broad market move.=C2=A0 Over the few days =
in November, Alameda=E2=80=99s assets fell roughly 50%; BTC fell about 15%-=
-only 30% as much as Alameda=E2=80=99s assets=E2=80=93and QQQ didn=E2=80=99=
t move at all. As a result, the larger hedge that Alameda had finally put o=
n that summer didn=E2=80=99t end up helping.=C2=A0 It would have for every =
previous crash that year=E2=80=93but not for this one.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the course of November 7th and 8th, thing=
s went from stressful but mostly under control to clearly insolvent.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, Changpeng Zhao, the head of rival exc=
hange Binance, tweeted mean stuff about FTX=E2=80=99s FTT token, which coll=
apsed the value of that token. There was =E2=80=9Ca targeted attack on asse=
ts held by Alameda,=E2=80=9D in which its stuff collapsed =E2=80=94=C2=A0du=
e to an =E2=80=9Cattack=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 while Bitcoin and the Nasdaq hel=
d up fine.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some level this is crazy. FTX loaned billio=
ns of dollars of money =E2=80=94=C2=A0of real money, of customer money =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0to Alameda against a pile of assets with billions of dollar of =
nominal value, but those assets were mostly altcoins, mostly incredibly ris=
ky bets on the future of crypto. They could all go to zero in the blink of =
an eye, and some of them did. FTX loaned billions of dollars to Alameda aga=
inst assets that could, and did, evaporate because=C2=A0<em>CZ tweeted mean=
 things about them</em>. Oh but Alameda was hedged! It hedged by shorting=
=C2=A0<em>Apple</em>. It could only go bankrupt if its assets lost their va=
lue =E2=80=94=C2=A0because of a mean tweet =E2=80=94=C2=A0but Apple did not=
. What were the chances=C2=A0of that? Incredibly high! Come on.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still I guess it is sort of a defense? The def=
ense is: =E2=80=9CAlameda had assets, those assets had market values, I tho=
ught those values were real, I thought they were hedged, and the market mov=
ed against them. Sure=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>might think that Alameda=E2=80=
=99s assets were worthless magic beans, and that=E2=80=99s how it turned ou=
t, but at the time I was a naive believer, so I thought it was fine to lend=
 money against them.=E2=80=9D This is not a great story,<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a> but it=E2=80=99s a lot better than =E2=80=9CI just stole the money,=E2=
=80=9D and it seems to be what he is going with.</p>
