<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30232666.268518/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTEvZmluYW5jaWFsLWVuZ2luZWVyaW5nLXRoZS1kZWJ0LWNlaWxp=
bmc_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmN=
lPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTEyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cCac174ad4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked yesterday</a> about the idea=
 that the US Department of the Treasury should issue premium bonds to avoid=
 the debt ceiling. The idea is that the Treasury could issue a 10-year bond=
 with a $100 face amount and a 15.6% interest rate, and that bond would be =
worth about $200. It could sell the bond for $200, raising $200 in cash but=
 counting for only $100 against the debt ceiling. If you buy that bond, you=
 pay $200 now and get back only $100 in 10 years, but you get $15.60 per ye=
ar in interest over those 10 years, which makes it worth it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People raised a couple of objections that I wa=
nt to quickly discuss here. First of all, a lot of people worry about the t=
ax treatment. If you buy a $200 Treasury for $200, and you get 3.6% interes=
t ($7.20 per year) and your $200 back at maturity, you pay tax on that $7.2=
0 of annual interest but not on the $200 you get back at the end. If you bu=
y a $100 Treasury for $200, and you get 15.6% interest ($15.60 per year) an=
d $100 back at maturity, you pay tax on the $15.60 of annual interest. More=
 of your payments are characterized as taxable income rather than non-taxab=
le return of principal, which seems bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in fact the tax treatment is basically sen=
sible: The tax code lets you <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/30232666.268518/aHR0cHM6Ly9zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tL3N0YXRpYy5jb250=
ZW50cmVzLmNvbS9tZWRpYS9kb2N1bWVudHMvOTkwMDg2YTYtZDg3ZS00NmRmLWJkYjQtNjgxNTU=
0OTY5ZWU1LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0cd6f123" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> deduct the prem=
ium</a> that you paid from your taxes. If you pay $200 for a $100 bond, you=
 paid $100 of premium, which you can amortize and deduct from your taxable =
income over the life of the bond. Oversimplifying , you deduct $10 per year=
 for 10 years, so your taxable interest income is $15.60 minus $10 equals $=
5.60 per year, more or less the right amount.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a> There are some <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30232666.268518/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzI2LzEuM=
TcxLTQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6440bae9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> elections to make</a>, =
and I am certainly not giving you tax advice, and this is probably a bit mo=
re annoying than just getting normal interest payments. But, no, the premiu=
m bond is not dramatically more tax-inefficient than a normal bond.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, there is a timing worry. The way this =
works is that Treasury would issue new premium bonds to pay back old bonds =
and raise extra money: A $100 bond comes due, Treasury replaces it with a n=
ew $100 high-interest bond, it sells the high-interest bond for $200, it pa=
ys off the old bond and=C2=A0keeps the extra $100 to pay for expenses. But =
if it has $200 of expenses, that doesn=E2=80=99t work: You need to be doing=
 enough new premium bond issuance to cover all the costs, or you need to st=
art well before reaching the debt ceiling to build up some cash cushion.=C2=
=A0In fact, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/302326=
66.268518/aHR0cHM6Ly9maXNjYWxkYXRhLnRyZWFzdXJ5Lmdvdi9kYXRhc2V0cy9tb250aGx5L=
XRyZWFzdXJ5LXN0YXRlbWVudC9zdW1tYXJ5LW9mLXJlY2VpcHRzLW91dGxheXMtYW5kLXRoZS1k=
ZWZpY2l0LXN1cnBsdXMtb2YtdGhlLXUtcy1nb3Zlcm5tZW50/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6=
34a1a36" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> Treasury=E2=80=99s monthly flows</a> vary but tend to ran=
ge from about a $300 billion surplus (April, tax day) to about a $430 billi=
on deficit (September); roughly $400 billion of Treasuries mature each mont=
h.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a> So it does not seem implausible that Treasury could cover its monthly =
expenses by issuing premium bonds worth 200 cents on the dollar, even if it=
 didn=E2=80=99t start much before hitting the limit.</p>
